The relatively newer self-centeredness and selflessness happiness model (SSHM) (Dambrun & Ricard, 2011) brings together many of the assumptions underlying eudaimonic well-being and self-determination theories. According to SSHM, hedonic and eudaimonic happiness are based on the way individuals perceive themselves. The self can be perceived as seemingly rigid, permanent, and independent, which supports a self-centered psychological functioning (e.g., how we feel, think, and behave). On the other hand, the self can be perceived as a permeable, interdependent, and flexible entity, which favors a selfless psychological functioning.
